API
========
Rest API

To horten a URL, POST endpoint to take in the long URL and custom alias and expiration date.
Using POST here is to create a new entry in data mapping.

POST /urls
{
  "long_url": "https://www.example.com/some/very/long/url",
  "custom_alias": "optional_custom_alias",
  "expiration_date": "optional_expiration_date"
}

-> return
{
  "short_url": "http://short.ly/abc123"
}

For redirection, GET endpoint that takes in the short and redirect to the original long URL
GET /{short_code}
-> HTTP 302 Redirect to the original long URL

#HTTP status should be 201 Created, not 200 OK
#unless a custom_alias collision is detected, in which case they return a 409 Conflict.



High-level design
=================
Client -(post)
Server(Generate shortURL, Save to db)
db(alias, original url, creationTime, expirationTime, createdBy)

Client: user interact through web/mobile app
Server: receive requests and handle logic like creation&validation
DB: Stores the mapping, expiration date.

When a user submit the URL and the client sends a POST request.
(1) Server receives the request and validates URL (is-url lib)
Optionally, check the long URL is already shortened.
Same long URL may separate expiration dates, independent analytics or custom aliases.

(2) If the URL is valid, generate a short code. custom alias could be short code(avoid duplication).
Prefixing generated codes with a character that aliases can't use.

(3) Insert the URL to db, storing the short code, long URL and expiration date.

(4) Return the short URL to the client.


User should be able to access the original URL by using the shortened URL.

Available in the domain, localhost/abc123 if is abc123.

Client POST /url Get/{shortCode}

Server Write(generate short URL/ save to db) Read(look up original url in DB/ return 302 redirect)

Database (short url code/ original url/ expiration time/ creation time/ created by)

When a user access a shortened URL, the following process occurs:

(1) User's browser sends a GET request to our server with the short code
(2) Server receives this request and look up in DB
(3) If the short code is found and hasn't expired, the server retries the long URL. For expired URLs return 410
(4) The server then sends an HTTP redirect response to the user's browser.

For cleanup, background job periodically to delete expired rows from DB. Cache TTL to match or be shorter
than URL expiration times so stale entries are automatically evicted.

301 (permanent redirect):
HTTP/1.1 301 moved permanently
Location: https://

302 (found): This indicated the resource is temporarily located at a different URL.
Browser do not cache this response.
HTTP/1.1 302 Found
Location: https://www.original-long-url.com

In either case, browser will automatically follow the redirect to the original long URL

For a URL shortener, 302 redirect is often preferred because:
(1) It gives more control over the redirection process, allowing update or expire links.
(2) Prevent browsers from caching, for the change in the future.
(3) It allows to track click statistics for short URL

